NOTES: 
Created Date: Mar 20 2015  3:54PM
Look for  an Analytics Product Manager - 

I've spoken to Liz and I have a little more clarity on what to expect from your interview tomorrow. 

The role is in the midst of being signed off, so when they see the right person they will be able to move, the right person is€¦ 

Ideally Liz is looking for someone who is technically orientated and who has very good technical aptitude and problem solving skills.  That would mean they generally look for someone with an engineering background, but it is the problem solving mindset that will be key.  

The team you would be joining is two years old, the project you would be working on is definitely on the BI side and you would work on setting up data platforms with 40 terabytes of data, transpose it and then create infrastructure. Then you will build out self-service platform which will be used by the analysts. I.e taking an unstructured environment and to come in and create structure. This will require strong skills around the BI analytics sector and will be very commercially heavy. 

This is a senior role probably more a kin to a product manager position. It will entail around 30% programming and 70% management. The technical environment that they use is Hadoop/hive and DB2 (which they are migrating away from to Teradata.)  On the visualisation front they use Tableau and Bespoke Javascript. They have specified they would be looking for people with advanced SQL. In addition, you will have a lot of stakeholder exposure and must be able to present ideas very clearly. 

The branch of Expedia that you would be working for is  Expedia Affiliate Network, (http://www.expediaaffiliate.com/index.php)  they are a B2B site who have customers such as; Lastminute.com, Groupon, American Airlines.
